Most Californians would agree that the hills and canyons are among he
most desirable places to live.  But these wild, yet settled, places at
the edge of the metropolis are the properties most threatened by
wildfire.

While little can be done to control the natural fires that occur,
homeowners can change their approach to landscaping and help improve
the chances of their homes and property surviving a brush fire.

While no plant is fireproof, some are more flammable than others.  A
line of defense against fire can be designed in the landscaping by
carefully selecting the plants that that will go in the garden around
the home.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d41"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA052289-0050"
SELECTOR="G"
SUMMARIZER="D">  

In Yellowstone National Park last summer's spectacular season of fire
scorched enough timber and meadow to rival Rhode Island in size.
Despite infernos that whipped through the treetops like blast
furnaces, most of the pristine landscape emerged unscathed.

Spring has come and arguments still rage over the impact of the fires
on wildlife, the conduct of officials responsible for monitoring the
blazes.  While the response from tourists is still questionable, the
park is bracing for an unprecedented onslaught of scientists looking
into fire behavior patterns, its effects on grizzly bears, fisheries,
grasslands and the nesting status of bald eagles.</SUM>

